HEADWORD: Proscenium
<hw>Pro*sce"ni*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Proscenia</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/; <?/
before + <?/ a tent, a wooden stage, the stage. See
<er>Scene</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anc. Theater)</fld> <def>The
part where the actors performed; the stage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Modern Theater)</fld> <def>The part of the stage in
front of the curtain; sometimes, the curtain and its
framework.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- <col><b>proscenium arch</b></col>, <cd>the framework around the
front of the stage in a theater.</cd> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proscolex</ent>⟦br⟧
